<title>Porcupine hunting </title>
<summary>An account of the hunting of porcupine and the practices that ensure its success (such as the treatment of their bones). The hunter is &apos;worked on&apos; by the women before he goes to seek porcupine. The porcupine goes about only at night and remains inside its hole when the place is bright. </summary><comments>1) p.7375v: |han≠kass&apos;o experienced these practices himself, 2) p.7377v: an explanation of the term &apos;decayed arm&apos;, 3) p.7379v: notes on trees in Bushmanland (including the Krieboom), 4) p.7381v: an explanation of the |xam term <i>kua kua ssi-kuiten, </i>which is applied to the porcupine (and the<i> |gipp,</i> or Proteles), 5) p.7386v: an explanation of the term &apos;it becomes white&apos;, 6) p.7388v: (5 September 1878) on rainfall and the abundance of food (&apos;laying down plenty&apos;), 7) p.7390v: the |xam name for the openings in the porcupine&apos;s tail that make a rattling sound, 8) p.7391v: (4 September 1878) the behaviour of the &apos;summer&apos;s porcupine&apos;, 9) See also <i>The little porcupine</i>, 10) This story is found in Book VIII-16</comments><date>31 August (started) – 4 September (finished on or about) 1878</date><storypages>7376-7393</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>hunting</kw><subkw>of porcupine</subkw></keyword>
